\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
High EBIDTA/EV.
 EBIDTA is a number you get when you add money lost to interest, taxes,
 depreciation, and amortization back to net income.
 Those four expense categories can be misleading when trying to compare
 companies, because finance and accounting methods vary widely from place
 to place.
 Thus, EBIDTA strips out those vagaries to look at raw profitability.
 EV is more accurate than market capitalization because somebody buying
 the whole company would need to pay its enterprise value, not its market
 cap.
 They would bank its cash but become responsible for its debt.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Best growth measures
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Relative Price Strength.
 In the short term, Newton's first law of motion seems to apply to large
 stocks as well as physical objects: prices in motion tend to stay in motion.
 The winners keep winning and the losers keep loosing.
 O'Shaughnessy concluded that "relative strength is among the only pure
 growth factors that actually beats the market consistently, and by a wide
 margin." He believes the reason is that it "conveys different information
 about the prospects of a stock and is a much better indicator than factors
 such as earnings growth rates.
 Many look at the disappointing results of buying stocks with the highest
 earnings gains and wonder why they differ from the best price performers.
 First, price momentum is the market putting its money where its mouth is.
 Second, the common belief that stocks with strong relative strength also
 have the highest P/E ratios or earnings growth is incorrect.
 When you look at the top performers over time, you find that they are rarely
 the highest valued in terms of P/E or P/S." The only time when price momentum
 did not work were bubble market tops and bear market bottoms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So, except for moments of extreme optimism and initial recoveries from extreme
 pessimism, buy stocks with the best 6-month relative price strength.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
