\begin_layout Itemize
(Howard Marks) Investing can't be reduced to an algorithm and turned over
 to a computer.
 Even the best investors don't get it right every time.
 The reasons are simple.
 No rule always works.
 The environment isn't controllable, and circumstances rarely repeat exactly.
 Psychology plays a major role in markets, and because it's highly variable,
 cause-and-effect relationships aren't reliable.
 An investment approach may work for a while, but eventually the actions
 it calls for will change the environment, meaning a new approach is needed.
 And if others emulate an approach, that will blunt its effectiveness.
 Investing, like economics, is more art than science.
 And that means it can get a little messy.
 Investment approach must be intuitive and adaptive rather than fixed and
 mechanistic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(Philip Fisher) In occasional cases it may take as much as five years for
 investments to demonstrate their real merit.
 Usually it does not take that long.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(Peter Lynch) However a stock come to your attention, the discovery is not
 a buy signal.
 What you've got so far is simply a lead to a story that has to be developed.
 You have to treat the initial information as if it were an anonymous and
 intriguing tip.
 This will keep you from buying a stock just because you've seen something
 you (or someone else) like.
 Developing the story is really not difficult: at most it will take a couple
 of hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
(Peter Lynch) You don't have to make money on every stock you pick.
 In Lynch experience, 6/10 winners in a portfolio can produce a satisfying
 results.
 All you need is a few big winners and the pluses will overwhelm the minuses
 from the stocks that don't work out as expected.
 You only have to find 1 big winner out of 11.
 The more right you are about any one stock, the more wrong you can be on
 all the others and still triumph as an investor.
\end_layout

