\begin_layout Itemize
In recent years, "smart beta" (also known as Strategic Beta, New Beta, Advanced
 Beta, or Beta plus) ETFs have became a hot product.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Smart beta managers create their own indexes - not, in fact, indexes in
 the traditional sense, but active strategies claiming to be indexes.
 They focus on weighting portfolios by so-called factors (some criteria)
 - stocks with similar forces driving their returns.
 Rather than weighting portfolio holdings by their market capitalization,
 they may focus on a single factor (value, momentum, size, ...) or may use
 a combination of factors such as corporate revenues, cash flows, profits,
 and dividends.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a concept, smart beta is not a terrible idea, nor is it a world-changing
 one.
 Smart beta ETF managers rely on computers to parse heavily mined past data
 on stocks that will enable fund managers to identify factors that can be
 easily packaged as ETFs.
 The goal is to create great profits for the manager by gathering the assets
 of investors seeking a performance edge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
William Sharpe, professor of finance at Stanford University and Nobel laureate
 in economist: 
\emph on
"Smart beta is stupid...It is quite remarkable that people think that somehow
 a scheme that weights stocks differently than capitalization can dominate
 a capitalization-weighted index...New paradigms come and go.
 Betting against the market (and spending a considerable amount of money
 to do so) is indeed likely to be a hazardous undertaking." 
\end_layout

