 How much money trades in the stock on a given day; this determines liquidity.
 This measure is of most interest to small cap investors.
 They look for low daily volume, because that means that mutual funds will
 stay away until the volume starts increasing.
 When it does, funds might buy in and drive the volume and price even higher.
 Large cap investors don't pay much attention to daily volume because it
 is always big.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sales.
 When sales and earnings grow quickly, share price tends to follow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Company health 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
New Profit Margin.
 High net profit margin is one of Warren Buffet's requirements for investing
 in a company.
 Effectiveness of its operation.
 How much of its earnings does a company keep? Follow the trend from 5 years
 ago and projected figures for current year and the next one.
 Any company in your sheet should have a net profit margin in the top 20%
 of its industry.
 These are leaders.
 But typical profit margin can change from industry to industry.
 Airlines generally have negative profit margins.
 Most commodity retailers such as supermarkets, auto parts stores, cheap
 clothing stores, and consumer electronics stores have net profit margins
 below 5%.
 Bigger is always better.
 Especially if it grows each year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cash and Total Debt.
 Ideally lots of cash and little or no debt.
 Later we'll use ratios to make sure the levels of cash and debt are acceptable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Stock health
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sales per Share.
 Try to capture the trend over the past 5 years.
 For growth companies, list only those that have increased sales per share
 in each of the past 5 years and are projected to increase them again current
 year and next.
 And ideally, it is very good also for value companies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cash Flow per Share.
 You want this positive and big.
 Capture the trend over the past 5 years.
 And projections for the next year.
 Especially for growth companies, this number must be increasing over the
 past 5 years - in each year.
 And its projections too.
 For value companies, it is optional but ideal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Earnings per Share.
 Growth investors insist on an increasing EPS.
 Check the trend over the past 5 years and 1 year predictions.
 With growth companies, it is required to be increasing, and with value
 stocks, a super discount is often accompanied by a dip in earnings.
 Occasionally, however, something else hammers a stock's price and earnings
 remain constant or increase.
 In that case, you're really getting a bargain.
 With value stocks, use your own judgment to decide on an up or down arrow
 based on whether the current number is an overall increase from 5 years
 ago, whether the increase is large or small, and by the projected earnings
 per share for this year and next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Dividend Yield.
 A high number is the deciding factor used in the Dow dividend strategies
 and was proven to work among large companies in James O'Shaughnessy's study
 of stock market history.
 It's very important figure to large-company investors.
 You can track the 5 year trend.
 Small-company investors ignore dividend yield because small companies don't
 usually declare dividends and therefore have yields of zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Return on Equity.
 It shows what a company has earned with the money people have invested
 in it.
 Net income divided by total shareholders' equity and you come up with a
 percentage.
 Warren Buffett likes this measurement because if gives a clear picture
 of what a company does with its profits.
 If a company gets bigger every year, it will probably earn more money.
 But investors should ask, does it earn enough additional money to support
 its larger size? Return on equity answers that.
 If a company can maintain a high return on equity as it grows, you know
 that management is directing profits wisely.
 Some people like to see ROE at least 20% maintained or improved over the
 years.
 Occasionally, value investors will accept low or negative ROEs in companies
 they think are about to make a change for the better.
 Steady ROE - company continues returning substantial profits to investors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Insider Buys/Ownership.
 You want to own companies that are owned by insiders, because if people
 who run the place have a material interest in its success, they're more
 likely to do a better job.
 You shouldn't pay attention to insider sells.
 For small cap investors, insider ownership is of particular importance
 because a lot of small companies are just starting out and management is
 a crucial factor in their success.
 Some people like small companies to have at least 20% insider ownership.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stock Buyback.
 It's great to see a company buying its stock back.
 There will be fewer shares outstanding, which improves supply-demand ratio
 and should increase the share price eventually.
\end_layout

