\series bold
Past performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
EPS rank.
 Take EPS for the two most recent quarters and compute their percentage
 change from the same 2 quarters a year ago.
 That result is combined and averaged with each company's five-year earnings
 growth record.
 The final figures for each company are compared with each other.
 Investor's Business Daily computes this metric.
 This measure is most important to growth investors because they look for
 consistently strong earnings and for the company to exceed expectations.
 Value investors like earnings, too, but they'll often buy a company with
 struggling earnings if it means the stock is enough of a bargain.
 Growth investors should insist on EPS rank of 85 or better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Relative Price Strength Rank.
 This measure looks at the stock's price performance in the latest 12 months.
 It simply reports the hard numbers and answers the question, how did this
 stock perform compared with all others? Investor's Business Daily updates
 the numbers daily.
 This metric is the most interested to growth investors.
 Value investors have no requirement for relative price strength because
 it would preclude bargain companies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Five-Year Sales and Earnings Gain.
 With small companies, strong sales and earnings are essential.
 The typical requirement is for them to have grown at least 25% over the
 past year.
 And we are looking at 5-year history here.
 For larger companies, it's good to see at least 10% increase, but for smaller,
 it can be at least 15% - annual sales and earnings increases.
 Try to stick with strong sales and earnings even if you're a value investor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Five-Year Price Appreciation.
 Take the high price from five years ago and compare it with the current
 price.
 Regardless to your preference on value or growth investing, it's good to
 know what happened to a stock in the past 5 years.
\end_layout

