\begin_layout Itemize
Current P/E.
 Value investors want to pay as little as they can for each dollar of earnings;
 growth investors don't care that much.
 But P/E ratio that's fairly priced will equal its growth rate.
 Growth rate of earnings.
 The current P/E should be at or below the five/year average P/E.
 That keeps you from buying in just after the company has broken into higher
 trading territory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Average P/E.
 Relevant for comparing with current P/E.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
P/S.
 Investors recognize its superiority over P/E for valuing stocks.
 P/S is often a more accurate measure of a company's value because sales
 can't be manipulated as easily as earnings.
 Also, the measure helps even growth investors identify companies that are
 selling below their potential.
 Even growth companies are best purchased cheap.
 It's fine to stay with a ratio below 2 but this is an ideal, not a requirement.
 Sometimes companies that are growing quickly show high P/S ratios but their
 share prices keep rising.
 History suggests, however, that a low P/S is a good sign.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
P/B.
 This is the second most common valuation measure following P/E.
 It tells how much you're paying for the actual assets of the company.
 But it isn't worth much to some people.
 They care a lot more about a company's use of its equipment to earn money
 than about the auction value of that equipment.
 They want the skill of human beings to turn the output of equipment into
 profit.
 That's the point of investing.
 Growth investors don't care at all about P/B, but value investors like
 to see it less than 1.
 Benjamin Graham recommended investing in companies with a P/B less than
 0.66.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Current Ratio.
 Just divide the current assets by current liabilities.
 The more assets a company has in relation to its liabilities, the better
 it's able to handle ugly surprises.
 Simply because it owns more than it owes - a situation everybody prefers.
 Try to invest in companies of at least current ratio of 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Price-to-Cash-Flow.
 Bill Miller called this "the single best predictor of excess return".
 Healthy businesses generate cash.
 Low number means high cash flow yield.
 Some people like to see P/CF of less than 5, but that's just a rough guideline.
 You can also compare it with 3/5-year average.
\end_layout

